Disclaimer: I haven&#x27;t looked at the code, I&#x27;m making an educated guess here.<p>I think it&#x27;s implemented like this:<p><pre><code>    function renderPage($stories) {
        renderHeaders();
        renderStories($stories);
        renderMoreLink(storeLink(function() {
                    renderPage(next30($stories));
                }));
    }

    function handleLinkClicked($id) {
        $code = fetchLink($id);
        $code();
    }
</code></pre>
Using storeLink() you save a <i>function</i>, than can be later executed when user clicked a particular link (remember, HN runs as a single process and does not restart itself every time like say, PHP does). This function remembers the context in which it was created - in this case, <i>$stories</i> variable - so all the data required to fulfil the request at later time gets stored with the function.
